texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: Brewing a Double-Espresso, a 10 Ounce Mug of American Coffee, or a Latte:
texts.text: Brewing a Double-Espresso, a 10 Ounce Mug of American Coffee, or a Latte:

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 1 Remove the plunger and the cap from the chamber.
texts.text: 1 Remove the plunger and the cap from the chamber.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 2 Put a filter in the cap and twist it onto the chamber.
texts.text: 2 Put a filter in the cap and twist it onto the chamber.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 3 on a sturdy mug.
texts.text: 3 on a sturdy mug.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: Stand the chamber
texts.text: Stand the chamber

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 4 Put two AeroPress scoops of fine-drip grind coffee into the chamber.
texts.text: 4 Put two AeroPress scoops of fine-drip grind coffee into the chamber.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 5 Pour hot water slowly into the chamber up to the number 2. Use 175 o F (80 o C) water for the very best taste.
texts.text: 5 Pour hot water slowly into the chamber up to the number 2. Use 175 o F (80 o C) water for the very best taste.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 6 Mix the water and coffee with the stirrer for about 10 seconds.
texts.text: 6 Mix the water and coffee with the stirrer for about 10 seconds.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 7 Wet the rubber seal and insert the plunger into the chamber. Gently press down about a quarter of an inch and maintain that pressure for about 20 to 30 seconds until the plunger bottoms on the coffee. Gentle pressure is the key to easy AeroPressing.
texts.text: 7 Wet the rubber seal and insert the plunger into the chamber. Gently press down about a quarter of an inch and maintain that pressure for about 20 to 30 seconds until the plunger bottoms on the coffee. Gentle pressure is the key to easy AeroPressing.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 8 You've just made a double espresso. For American coffee, top-off the mug with hot water.  For a latte, top-off the mug with hot milk.
texts.text: 8 You've just made a double espresso. For American coffee, top-off the mug with hot water.  For a latte, top-off the mug with hot milk.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: Cleanup and Storage:
texts.text: Cleanup and Storage:

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Remove the cap and set it aside.  Push the plunger to eject the "puck" of spent grounds into the trash (or save for compost or plant food.)
texts.text: Remove the cap and set it aside.  Push the plunger to eject the "puck" of spent grounds into the trash (or save for compost or plant food.)

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Rinse and/or brush away any grounds left on the rubber seal.  The seal has already wiped your chamber clean, so no further cleanup is needed.
texts.text: Rinse and/or brush away any grounds left on the rubber seal.  The seal has already wiped your chamber clean, so no further cleanup is needed.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Always eject the puck right after brewing and store your AeroPress with the plunger pushed all the way through or completely removed. Storing the seal uncompressed will keep your seal air-tight for years.
texts.text: Always eject the puck right after brewing and store your AeroPress with the plunger pushed all the way through or completely removed. Storing the seal uncompressed will keep your seal air-tight for years.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: HINTS
texts.text: HINTS

texts.label: text
texts.orig: You can press using from 1 to 4 scoops of grounds.  Each AeroPress scoop makes a single espresso or 5 ounces of American coffee. Fill the chamber with hot water to the number corresponding to the number of scoops.
texts.text: You can press using from 1 to 4 scoops of grounds.  Each AeroPress scoop makes a single espresso or 5 ounces of American coffee. Fill the chamber with hot water to the number corresponding to the number of scoops.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: You can make a full carafe of coffee using your AeroPress in less time than it takes to brew a pot of drip coffee.  Two 3-scoop or 4-scoop pressings, topped off with hot water will fill most vacuum carafes.
texts.text: You can make a full carafe of coffee using your AeroPress in less time than it takes to brew a pot of drip coffee.  Two 3-scoop or 4-scoop pressings, topped off with hot water will fill most vacuum carafes.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: If you grind your own, use the AeroPress funnel to transfer the coffee from the grinder to the AeroPress chamber.  A scoop of beans equals a scoop of grounds.
texts.text: If you grind your own, use the AeroPress funnel to transfer the coffee from the grinder to the AeroPress chamber.  A scoop of beans equals a scoop of grounds.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: If pressing is too difficult, try pressing more gently and/or using a coarser grind.  For single-scoop pressings you can use the finest grind you can get.
texts.text: If pressing is too difficult, try pressing more gently and/or using a coarser grind.  For single-scoop pressings you can use the finest grind you can get.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The plunger can be used to measure water.
texts.text: The plunger can be used to measure water.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Two thousand filters use about as much paper as one city newspaper, so you needn't feel guilty about discarding filters.  But you can also re-use each filter many times just by brushing it off under running water.  The choice is up to you. When re-using a filter, remove the plunger and twist the cap containing the wet filter onto the chamber.  This will keep it flat as it dries and you'll be ready for the next pressing.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS
texts.text: FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS

texts.label: text
texts.orig: What grind should I use? We recommend using "fine drip" grind.  If you use a blade grinder, run it for 20 to 30 seconds.  For single-scoop pressings, you can even use espresso grind. Using a fine grind helps brew very rich flavor.
texts.text: What grind should I use? We recommend using "fine drip" grind.  If you use a blade grinder, run it for 20 to 30 seconds.  For single-scoop pressings, you can even use espresso grind. Using a fine grind helps brew very rich flavor.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Why do you recommend brewing with 175°F (80°C) water? All of our tasters, from coffee lovers to coffee professionals, preferred 175°F. It delivers a smooth, rich brew.  Hotter water increases bitterness and acidity.
texts.text: Why do you recommend brewing with 175°F (80°C) water? All of our tasters, from coffee lovers to coffee professionals, preferred 175°F. It delivers a smooth, rich brew.  Hotter water increases bitterness and acidity.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: How do I heat water to the right temperature?
texts.text: How do I heat water to the right temperature?

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Microwave oven: Use a thermometer and experiment to determine the time needed to heat the desired amount of water to 175°F. In the future, heat the same amount of water for that time.
texts.text: Microwave oven: Use a thermometer and experiment to determine the time needed to heat the desired amount of water to 175°F. In the future, heat the same amount of water for that time.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Kettle: Poke a thermometer in the spout of your kettle and heat until it reads 175°F.
texts.text: Kettle: Poke a thermometer in the spout of your kettle and heat until it reads 175°F.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Three-quarters of the time to boil: Heat the desired amount of water in a kettle or microwave oven and measure the time it takes to boil.  Heating the same amount of water for three-quarters of that time will reach the right temperature.
texts.text: Three-quarters of the time to boil: Heat the desired amount of water in a kettle or microwave oven and measure the time it takes to boil.  Heating the same amount of water for three-quarters of that time will reach the right temperature.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Instant hot water: If you have instant hot water in your kitchen, it's probably close to 175°. If necessary, take a few minutes to set it.
texts.text: Instant hot water: If you have instant hot water in your kitchen, it's probably close to 175°. If necessary, take a few minutes to set it.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Some water drips through the coffee and filter before I stir.    Is that OK? That is perfectly normal and will not affect the final brew. If a lot of water runs through before stirring, remember to use fine-drip grind and to pour the water in slowly, particularly for the first few seconds to wet the grounds.
texts.text: Some water drips through the coffee and filter before I stir.    Is that OK? That is perfectly normal and will not affect the final brew. If a lot of water runs through before stirring, remember to use fine-drip grind and to pour the water in slowly, particularly for the first few seconds to wet the grounds.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Am I doing something wrong if it is hard to press? Pressing hard compresses the puck of coffee and blocks the flow. Gentle is the key. Gently press the plunger down about a quarter inch and then maintain that amount of pressure as the plunger sinks down to the grounds.  Let the air pressure in the chamber do the work.  If you press gently and pressing is still difficult, try a coarser grind.
texts.text: Am I doing something wrong if it is hard to press? Pressing hard compresses the puck of coffee and blocks the flow. Gentle is the key. Gently press the plunger down about a quarter inch and then maintain that amount of pressure as the plunger sinks down to the grounds.  Let the air pressure in the chamber do the work.  If you press gently and pressing is still difficult, try a coarser grind.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: If I am just making a single cup, can I push all the water for the cup through the press? Yes, but when you push a full cup of water past the grounds it extracts bitterness.  Diluting your espresso-sized pressing with hot water makes a much smoother brew.
texts.text: If I am just making a single cup, can I push all the water for the cup through the press? Yes, but when you push a full cup of water past the grounds it extracts bitterness.  Diluting your espresso-sized pressing with hot water makes a much smoother brew.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: How do I make a latte? A latte is espresso mixed with hot milk.  You can add hot milk to the espresso or you can add cold milk and then heat the latte in a microwave oven.
texts.text: How do I make a latte? A latte is espresso mixed with hot milk.  You can add hot milk to the espresso or you can add cold milk and then heat the latte in a microwave oven.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: How do I make a cappuccino?
texts.text: How do I make a cappuccino?

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Cappuccino is simply espresso capped with a layer of foamed milk.  The traditional way of foaming and heating milk is with steam.  But those who have tried battery powered stirrers agree that they do a great job of foaming milk and are very easy to use and clean.
texts.text: Cappuccino is simply espresso capped with a layer of foamed milk.  The traditional way of foaming and heating milk is with steam.  But those who have tried battery powered stirrers agree that they do a great job of foaming milk and are very easy to use and clean.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Can I clean the AeroPress in the dishwasher? You can in the top shelf, but a simple rinse is entirely sufficient because the plunger wipes the chamber clean.
texts.text: Can I clean the AeroPress in the dishwasher? You can in the top shelf, but a simple rinse is entirely sufficient because the plunger wipes the chamber clean.
